metadata.name: All The Way #161
metadata.description:
"All the Way" is a visually stunning and dynamic generative art piece that is sure to make a striking addition to any art collection. Created using the programming language p5js, this artwork is truly one of a kind and cannot be replicated.

The vibrant colors, fluid shapes, and dynamic movement in "All the Way" make it an ideal centerpiece for any space. The constantly shifting shapes and colors create a sense of energy and motion that will draw the eye and captivate the viewer. This piece is perfect for anyone who loves abstract art or is looking for something unique and eye-catching to add to their collection.

Additionally, the theme of "All the Way" is one that is sure to resonate with many people. The artwork represents the flow of life, the power of creativity, and the endless possibilities that exist in the world around us. This makes it an ideal choice for anyone who values personal growth, exploration, and a sense of adventure.

Whether you're an art collector, an art enthusiast, or simply someone who appreciates beautiful and thought-provoking art, "All the Way" is a must-have addition to your collection. With its dynamic and abstract style, this piece is sure to spark conversations and inspire new ideas. Don't miss out on the chance to own a truly unique and captivating artwork that you will enjoy for years to come!

To save image press "s"
To save image in high quality add &print=2 or &print=3 in the live URL then press "s".

Note: Image can take a minute to render.

Created using p5js and p5js pattern
Created By Winston
Feb 2023

metadata.name: The Distant peaks #89
metadata.description:
The Distant Peaks is the first generative art release that combines my collection on Objkt:
"The Windless Summit and The Distant sea"

Since the beginning, I want to create a plotter printer or generative art style. but I don't have the basic knowledge to do creative coding, so I tried to replicate it with The Help of artificial intelligence and now I'm collaborating with @rosetta196 to help me experiment with the generative art area.

Each piece in this collection is a unique and intricate representation of the rugged peaks and sweeping vistas of mountains, as well as the calming of the ocean's waves. The colors, textures, and movements of the artwork are all meticulously crafted through code, with every detail carefully considered to capture the essence of these natural wonders.

The use of pure code to generate these landscapes serves to highlight the beauty and complexity of mathematics and computer programming. 
It is a testament to the power of technology and its ability to create stunning works of art that evoke deep emotions and inspire creativity.

As you gaze upon the art, you are drawn into a world of tranquility and natural beauty. The peacefulness of the mountains and the endless expanse of the ocean come to life, inviting you to explore and discover the wonders of the natural world. 
This art project is a celebration of the beauty of nature and the incredible potential of generative art.


by Samanta and Rosetta196 2023

metadata.name: Echoes of the Fractal Depths #8
metadata.description:
This project is an exploration of the Mandelbrot set, one of the most famous and recognizable fractal patterns in mathematics. The images you see are generated entirely through code. The Mandelbrot set is a complex and beautiful mathematical object, created through the iteration of simple equations. At its core, it represents the boundary between order and chaos.

's' to save

metadata.name: Coronado #141
metadata.description:
This series is about the beauty and charm of imperfection, chaos amidst order, and letting go. It's about knowing that however much control we think we may have, things can all fall apart or burst into something unexpectedly wonderful at any moment, even without our hands tightly on the reigns.

Please see fxtext article linked from main project page for more background on the project and rendering notes.

G : Toggle grain
S : Save current resolution
1 : 4000x5000

metadata.name: Vacuole #143
metadata.description:
Vacuole emerged from a cellular automaton sketch to which I come back from time to time to experiment with different rules and mechanisms.

To celebrate #fxhashturnsone, I wanted to look for alternative forms than the classical top-to-bottom/bottow-to-top scanline growing behaviour. Vocuole instead uses a grid of fields, where each field is initialized with different rules, growing directions and settings. The system combines two different variations: classical elementary cellular automata rules and a copy-pixel/plasma rule, which takes pixels from the neighborhood with a noise-controled offset like a stamp.

THREE.js.

Gravity's End depicts fictional worlds being warped, distorted, and in rare cases, shattered, due to extreme gravitational forces.

metadata.name: Over the Air #255
metadata.description:
During the last couple of decades, over the air television signals and antennas switched to digital, bringing with them a new form of static and distortion as the signal is broken up. "Over the Air" is inspired by these digital distortions, incorporating aspects of them into the same grid-like structure seen on the television. Additional patterns are combined in the grid with these distortions to create the final artwork.

Patterns for the individual blocks in the grid are divided into categories, and various amounts are picked for each work, with dozens of possible mixtures. Patterns can flow in different directions across the varied canvases. Distribution of these patterns across the grid varies from work to work, providing for different feels as they bunch together or spread apart.

metadata.name: Sugar & Splice #242
metadata.description:
'Sugar & Splice'

Vibrant somethings, full of flavor, dancing within conjoined boundaries.

Controls:
s: Saves an image of the canvas with the current settings
1-6: Scales the canvas size, from 1 (default, 2048px x 2792px) to 6 (12288px x  16752px)
g: Toggles grain texture
t: Toggles background transparency
f: Toggles fit to screen (layout and other factors will change based on the new size, but overall style, colors, etc will remain the same)
p: Shortcut for large print settings: disables the grain texture and scales the canvas to the largest setting
b: Toggles b-side

metadata.name: Crisis Worlds #136
metadata.description:
An abstract, generative illustration of impending planetary doom. Something, or someone, has sent the gas giants of the galaxy on a path toward destruction.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 2318 × 3000px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

Less common features
- Giant planets
- Inverted, light colors
- Umber/grey and mint green as the primary space colors
- Star trails are 50/50
